{"id":418,"date":"2021-06-29T15:57:28","date_gmt":"2021-06-29T15:57:28","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/?p=418"},"modified":"2022-09-30T11:18:08","modified_gmt":"2022-09-30T11:18:08","slug":"how-to-build-a-solar-system-project","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/coding-for-kids\/blog\/how-to-build-a-solar-system-project\/","title":{"rendered":"Scratch for Kids: Here&#8217;s How to Build a Solar System Project"},"content":{"rendered":"<h2>Introduction<\/h2>\n<p>Developed as a project of the Lifelong Kindergarten Group at the MIT Media Lab, the platform helps young people to apply creativity, reasoning and logic while working on collaborative projects.<\/p>\n<p>The core audience on the <a href=\"https:\/\/scratch.mit.edu\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Scratch website<\/a> is between the ages of 8 and 16 (with a peak at age 12), though there is a sizable group of adult participants as well.<\/p>\n<p>The name \u201cScratch\u201d itself highlights the idea of tinkering. The name comes from the scratching technique used by hip-hop disc jockeys, who tinker with music by spinning vinyl records back and forth with their hands, mixing music clips together in creative ways.<\/p>\n<a class=\"blog-ads-mid-banner\" href=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/register\/?utm_source=eu-blog-display-ads\"><img class=\"lazy aligncenter wp-image-1085 size-full\" style=\"filter: drop-shadow(rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2) 0px 2px 4px);\" data-src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/10\/blog-mid-ads1.png\" alt=\"Best Online Coding class for kids\" width=\"740\" height=\"276\" \/><\/a>\n<p>In Scratch Programming, the activity is similar: mixing together graphics, animations, photos, music, and sound. Overall, Scratch programming is easy for kids to use and understand.<\/p>\n<p>To help you better understand the Scratch platform, here is a step-by-step guide to creating a solar system using Scratch.<\/p>\n<p>So let\u2019s get started right away and have lots of fun along the way.<\/p>\n<h2><b>Step 1: Opening Scratch\u00a0<\/b><\/h2>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-shadow wp-image-442 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/1-1-1024x646.jpg\" alt=\"Scratch coding and programming platform\" width=\"600\" height=\"378\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/1-1-1024x646.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/1-1-300x189.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/1-1-768x484.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/1-1.jpg 1158w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Go to Google search. Type \u2018Scratch\u2019 in the search bar. Click on the first option that appears as pointed by an arrow in the image below.<\/p>\n<h2><b>Step 2: Creating a project<\/b><\/h2>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-shadow wp-image-443 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/2-1-1024x431.jpg\" alt=\"Creating a project on scratch\" width=\"600\" height=\"253\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/2-1-1024x431.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/2-1-300x126.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/2-1-768x323.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/2-1.jpg 1230w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Click on the create option as circled in the image below.<\/p>\n<h2><b>Step 3: Deleting default sprite<\/b><\/h2>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-shadow wp-image-444 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/3-1-1024x461.jpg\" alt=\"Deleting from scratch coding\" width=\"600\" height=\"270\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/3-1-1024x461.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/3-1-300x135.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/3-1-768x346.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/3-1-1536x692.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/3-1.jpg 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>By default, we will have a cat sprite option (sprite refers to an image in scratch). We don\u2019t need it as we are doing a solar system project. Delete it by clicking on the delete icon pointed by the red arrow.<\/p>\n<h2><b>Step 4: Choosing a backdrop<\/b><\/h2>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-shadow wp-image-445 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/4-1-1024x459.jpg\" alt=\"how to choose a backdrop on scratch platform\" width=\"600\" height=\"269\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/4-1-1024x459.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/4-1-300x134.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/4-1-768x344.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/4-1-1536x688.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/4-1.jpg 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Let\u2019s choose a background for our solar system now. Click on the <b>\u201cChoose a Backdrop\u201d<\/b> option at the bottom right corner as pointed in red.<\/p>\n<p>Type <b>\u201cStars\u201d<\/b> in the search bar and select the Stars backdrop to suit our project and add it.<\/p>\n<h2><b>Step 5: Adding sun sprite<\/b><\/h2>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-shadow wp-image-446 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/5-1-1024x549.jpg\" alt=\"Adding sun sprite on Scratch platform\" width=\"600\" height=\"321\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/5-1-1024x549.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/5-1-300x161.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/5-1-768x411.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/5-1.jpg 1430w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>The Solar System consists of the Sun and the planets. Now, let\u2019s add them to our project. Click on choose a sprite as pointed by the arrow.<\/p>\n<p>Select Sun from the search bar and add it as below.<\/p>\n<a class=\"blog-ads-mid-banner\" href=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/register\/?utm_source=eu-blog-display-ads\"><img class=\"lazy aligncenter wp-image-1085 size-full\" style=\"filter: drop-shadow(rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2) 0px 2px 4px);\" data-src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/10\/blog-mid-ads-2.png\" alt=\"Best Coding Course for K12 Kids\" width=\"740\" height=\"276\" \/><\/a>\n<h2><b>Step 6: Downloading planet sprites<\/b><\/h2>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-shadow wp-image-447 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/6-1-1024x460.jpg\" alt=\"Downloading planet sprites\" width=\"600\" height=\"270\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/6-1-1024x460.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/6-1-300x135.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/6-1-768x345.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/6-1-1536x690.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/6-1.jpg 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Let\u2019s add the other planets now. The other planet sprites are not available on Scratch by default. So, let\u2019s download them all from Google.<\/p>\n<p>To download a sprite, go to google search and type the names of individual planets. Click on their image and download it to your computer. Later, upload the sprite on Scratch.<\/p>\n<p>Let\u2019s add Mercury as an example. Type Mercury in google search. Click on images option. Select an image. Right click, select save image as option, and save the image.<\/p>\n<h2><b>Step 7: Uploading planet sprites<\/b><\/h2>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-shadow wp-image-448 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/7-1-1024x456.jpg\" alt=\"Uploading planet sprites on scratch \" width=\"600\" height=\"267\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/7-1-1024x456.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/7-1-300x134.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/7-1-768x342.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/7-1-1536x684.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/7-1.jpg 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Let\u2019s upload all the downloaded images of planets to Scratch now.<\/p>\n<p>First, let\u2019s take an example of Mercury. Go to Choose a Sprite option as we did while choosing the Sun sprite. Select upload a sprite option and select the mercury image from your computer.<\/p>\n<p>Select the Sun sprite and set size as 50. Similarly set size for Mercury as 30 or any size you like.<\/p>\n<h2><b>Step 8: Aligning sprites<\/b><\/h2>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-shadow wp-image-449 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/8-1-1024x463.jpg\" alt=\"Aligning sprites on scratch platform\" width=\"600\" height=\"271\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/8-1-1024x463.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/8-1-300x136.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/8-1-768x347.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/8-1-1536x694.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/8-1.jpg 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Let\u2019s add all the planets now and after that your project would look like the image below.<\/p>\n<p>9 sprites added from left to right: Sun, Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune.<\/p>\n<p>Align all the sprites in a straight line and resize them as necessary.<\/p>\n<h2><b>Step 9: Coding sun sprite for sound<\/b><\/h2>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-shadow wp-image-450 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/9-1-1024x461.jpg\" alt=\"Coding sun sprite for sound on scratch platform\" width=\"600\" height=\"270\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/9-1-1024x461.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/9-1-300x135.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/9-1-768x346.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/9-1.jpg 1502w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Now, let\u2019s start to code the Sun and the other planets one after another.<\/p>\n<p>To code for the Sun, first select the Sun sprite among other sprites.<\/p>\n<p>As pointed by the arrow in the image, add blocks as explained further.<\/p>\n<p>Under the code section, select the events option and then drag and drop the block named \u201cwhen clicked\u201d. Similarly, select the control option and drag and drop the block named \u201cforever\u201d.<\/p>\n<p>Next, click on the sounds option, select \u201cchoose a sound\u201d and choose any sound you like. Now, go back to the code option and under the sounds section, drag and drop the block named \u201cplay sound until done\u201d.<\/p>\n<h2><b>Step 10: Coding sun sprite to display name<\/b><\/h2>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-shadow wp-image-451 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/10-1-1024x458.jpg\" alt=\"Coding sun sprite to display name on block coding scratch programming\" width=\"600\" height=\"269\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/10-1-1024x458.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/10-1-300x134.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/10-1-768x344.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/10-1-1536x687.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/10-1.jpg 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Now, let\u2019s code the sprites to display names when clicked.<\/p>\n<p>Go to the events option under the code section, drag and drop the block named \u201cwhen this sprite clicked\u201d.<\/p>\n<p>Let\u2019s code the Sun sprite to display its name when clicked. To do that, go to the looks option, drag and drop the block named \u201csay hello for 2 seconds\u201d. Type \u201cHello, I am Sun\u201d instead of \u201chello\u201d in the above block.<\/p>\n<p>Click on the Run option (green flag). Click again on the Sun sprite and you will see it display \u201cHello, I am Sun\u201d as pointed by the arrow in the image below.<\/p>\n<a class=\"blog-ads-mid-banner\" href=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/register\/?utm_source=eu-blog-display-ads\"><img class=\"lazy aligncenter wp-image-1085 size-full\" style=\"filter: drop-shadow(rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2) 0px 2px 4px);\" data-src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/10\/blog-mid-ads1.png\" alt=\"Best Online Coding class for kids\" width=\"740\" height=\"276\" \/><\/a>\n<h2><b>Step 11: Coding planets to display names<\/b><\/h2>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-shadow wp-image-452 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/11-1-1024x456.jpg\" alt=\"Coding planets to display names on scratch\" width=\"600\" height=\"267\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/11-1-1024x456.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/11-1-300x134.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/11-1-768x342.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/11-1-1536x684.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/11-1.jpg 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Further, let\u2019s code for all other planets as well.<\/p>\n<p>Click on the Mercury sprite. Under the code section go to events, drag and drop the block \u201cwhen this sprite clicked\u201d. Next, go to events and drag the drop the block named \u201csay hello for 2 seconds\u201d. Replace the word \u201chello\u201d with \u201cHello, I am Mercury\u201d.<\/p>\n<h2><b>Step 12: Run and save the project<\/b><\/h2>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-shadow wp-image-453 aligncenter\" src=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/12-1-1024x462.jpg\" alt=\"how to Run and save the project on scratch\" width=\"600\" height=\"271\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/12-1-1024x462.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/12-1-300x135.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/12-1-768x347.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/12-1-1536x693.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/resources\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/06\/12-1.jpg 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Now, let\u2019s code similarly for all other planets. The only change would be to add the names of the respective planets in \u201cHello, I am ____\u201d block.<\/p>\n<p>After coding for all planets, click on the \u201cRun\u201d option (green flag). Now, click on each planet to display its name along with the sound playing in the background.<\/p>\n<p>To stop the project click on the \u201cRed\u201d button next to the \u201cRun\u201d button.<\/p>\n<p>Save the project by clicking on the \u201cUntitled\u201d option at the top left and rename it as \u201cSolar System\u201d.<\/p>\n<p>Kudos! You have successfully created the \u201cSolar System\u201d using Scratch!<\/p>\n<h2><b>Why teach Scratch programming for kids<\/b><\/h2>\n<p>Scratch is a great platform for kids to get started to learn to code. It\u2019s a stepping stone for curious and enthusiastic kids to explore the possibilities with programming.<\/p>\n<p>As children use Scratch to create and share interactive projects, they learn important mathematical and computational concepts, while also learning to think creatively, reason systematically, and work collaboratively\u2014essential skills for the 21st century.<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/courses\/scratch-programming\/\">Scratch programming for kids<\/a> not only prepares them for careers as professional programmers, but also nurtures the development of a new generation of creative, systematic thinkers who are comfortable using programming to express their ideas. Codingal offers the <a href=\"https:\/\/www.codingal.com\/\">best online coding course for k